_Free Monad or Tagless Final? How not to commit to a monad too early_ by _Adam Warski_
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This was the first time I saw [Adam](https://twitter.com/adamwarski) presenting, and was well worth it. My knowledge of [tagless final encoding](http://okmij.org/ftp/tagless-final/index.html) is... shallow, to say the least (and not like my knowledge of free is excellent, but is better) and I left this talk feeling like I learnt a lot. The best way to leave a talk, I think. I also found later that [Pere](https://twitter.com/pvillega) has a comparison of them, also adding the [Eff monad](https://github.com/atnos-org/eff) to the mix. 
Be sure to check his company’s ([SoftwareMill](https://softwaremill.com/blog/)) blog for a wealth of interesting posts. As well as subscribe to [ScalaTimes](http://scalatimes.com/), which they curate weekly. 

{{< figure src="AdamWarski.jpg" class="fig-wide" caption="♬ So Tagless can't you see, I want to break Free ♬">}}



_Farewell Any => Unit, Welcome Akka Typed!_ with _Heiko Seeberger_
------------------------------------------------------------------

I had read stuff by [Heiko](https://twitter.com/hseeberger?lang=en) (for instance, [a post on using akka-testkit](https://hseeberger.gitlab.io/2017/09/13/how-to-use-akka-testkit.html)), and had started having a look at the new typed APIs, but seeing it live-coded by the person who wrote a big part of it is priceless. Now, I need to rewrite my unfinished, unpublished ad server in akka-typed! 
I had already seen Daniela’s talk (was on the same slot) _[A pragmatic introduction to Category Theory](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ss149MsZluI)_ at Scala World earlier in the year (and, IIRC with longer time so it was almost a workshop, enjoy the video) so I skipped it. But can recommend, was excellent. 

